nsightful and nuanced analyses of Moorish clothing production and circulation shows that as well as being a sign of status and a marker of nobility, it also served to codify social tensions by deploying apparent Islamophobic discourses. Such luxurious value of clothing also sheds light on how sartorial legislation against the Moriscos was not only a form of cultural repression, but also a way to preclude their full integration into Iberian society. Moors Dressed as Moors challenges the traditional interpretations of the value of Moorish clothing in sixteenth and seventeenth-century Spain and how it articulated the relationships between Christians and Moriscos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMoriscosxClothingzIberian PeninsulaxHistoryy16th century. 0aMoriscosxClothingzIberian PeninsulaxHistoryy17th century. 0aMoriscoszIberian PeninsulaxEthnic identityxHistoryy16th century. 0aMoriscoszIberian PeninsulaxEthnic identityxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066594940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751358040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487513580423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487513580.jpg  a978-3-11-066594-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles